The Feriae Latinae, or Latin hohdays, were first appointed by Tarquin for one day, but after the expulsion of the kings they were continued for two, then for three, and at last for four days. They were kept with great solemnity on the Alban mountain. The epithet indictae marks them as movable, and appointed at the pleasure. of the consul, a circumstance which places them in direct opposition to the Statae Feriae, or fixed festivals of the Romans. Philip could go into the country during these holidays, as the courts were then shut.—79.
